but I don't go along with it.


1369
1:13:10,845 --> 1:13:14,932
Now, the boy was 5 feet 7 inches tall.
His father was 6'2...


1370
1:13:14,932 --> 1:13:17,185
That's a difference of seven inches.


1371
1:13:17,185 --> 1:13:19,937
It's a very awkward thing to stab down
into the chest of someone...


1372
1:13:19,937 --> 1:13:22,23
who's more than half a foot
taller than you are.


1373
1:13:22,23 --> 1:13:24,233
Give me that.


1374
1:13:24,233 --> 1:13:28,404
I'll give you a demonstration.
Somebody get up.


1375
1:13:28,404 --> 1:13:34,827
You...


1376
1:13:34,827 --> 1:13:37,622
I want you to watch this 'cause
I don't want to have to do it again.


1377
1:13:37,622 --> 1:13:40,458
I'll make myself about six
or seven inches shorter, okay?


1378
1:13:40,458 --> 1:13:51,385
- It's about right. Maybe a little more.
- Okay. A little more.


1379
1:13:51,385 --> 1:13:55,89
That's not funny.


1380
1:13:55,89 --> 1:14:0,394
Now, nobody's hurt. Right?


1381
1:14:0,394 --> 1:14:5,65
Right. Nobody hurt.


1382
1:14:5,65 --> 1:14:10,53
Now, this is the way I'd stab a man
who was taller than I was.


1383
1:14:10,53 --> 1:14:13,74
Look at the angle - down and in.


1384
1:14:13,74 --> 1:14:15,243
And this is the way it was done.


1385
1:14:15,243 --> 1:14:19,622
Now tell me I'm wrong.


1386
1:14:19,622 --> 1:14:23,126
- Down and in. I guess there's no argument.
- Hold it a minute, will ya?


1387
1:14:23,126 --> 1:14:25,962
Can you give me that?


1388
1:14:25,962 --> 1:14:27,964
Boy, I hate these things.


1389
1:14:27,964 --> 1:14:29,715
- Did you ever see a knife fight?
- No.


1390
1:14:29,715 --> 1:14:31,384
- You?
- No.


1391
1:14:31,384 --> 1:14:34,262
Anybody here ever see a knife fight?


1392
1:14:34,262 --> 1:14:37,14
Well, I have.
You know, on my back stoop...


1393
1:14:37,14 --> 1:14:39,559
the lot across the street, backyard.


1394
1:14:39,559 --> 1:14:42,61
Switchblades came
with the neighborhood where I lived.


1395
1:14:42,61 --> 1:14:45,398
It's funny I never thought of it before.
I guess you try to forget those things.


1396
1:14:45,398 --> 1:14:50,528
- How do you use a switchblade?
- Well, you'd never use it like this.


1397
1:14:50,528 --> 1:14:54,574
See, you use too much time
switching hands.


1398
1:14:54,574 --> 1:14:59,787
Here's how - underhanded.


1399
1:14:59,787 --> 1:15:2,915
Anyone who's ever used a switch knife
wouldn't handle it any other way.


1400
1:15:2,915 --> 1:15:5,626
- Are you sure?
- I'm sure.


1401
1:15:5,626 --> 1:15:7,545
That's why they're made to open like that.


1402
1:15:7,545 --> 1:15:10,256
- You'd say the boy was pretty handy with a knife?
- Mm-hmm.


1403
1:15:10,256 --> 1:15:13,509
You think he could have made
the kind of wound that killed his father?


1404
1:15:13,509 --> 1:15:17,513
No. Not with the experience he'd had
all his life handling these things.


1405
1:15:17,513 --> 1:15:19,599
I feel he'd have gone for him underhanded.


1406
1:15:19,599 --> 1:15:22,727
How do you know? Were you
in the room when the father was killed?


1407
1:15:22,727 --> 1:15:24,812
No. Neither was anybody else.


1408
1:15:24,812 --> 1:15:28,107
So what are you giving us all this
mumbo jumbo for? I don't believe it.


1409
1:15:28,107 --> 1:15:31,444
I don't think you can determine what type of
wound the boy might or might not have made...


1410
1:15:31,444 --> 1:15:34,155
simply because he knew
how to handle a knife.


1411
1:15:34,155 --> 1:15:36,574
What do you think?


1412
1:15:36,574 --> 1:15:38,743
- I don't know.
- What do you mean you don't know?


1413
1:15:38,743 --> 1:15:44,79
I don't know.


1414
1:15:44,79 --> 1:15:46,876
How about you?


1415
1:15:46,876 --> 1:15:50,713
I don't know about the rest of them, but I'm getting a
little tired of this yackety-yackin' back and forth.


1416
1:15:50,713 --> 1:15:54,258
It's gettin' us nowhere.
So I guess I'll have to break it up.


1417
1:15:54,258 --> 1:15:56,886
I change my vote to not guilty.


1418
1:15:56,886 --> 1:16:0,306
- You what?
- You heard me. I've had enough.


1419
1:16:0,306 --> 1:16:2,85
What do you mean you've had enough?
That's no answer!


1420
1:16:2,85 --> 1:16:6,896
Hey, listen. You just take care
of yourself, huh? You know?


1421
1:16:6,896 --> 1:16:10,942
He's right. That's not an answer.


1422
1:16:10,942 --> 1:16:13,986
What kind of a man are you?


1423
1:16:13,986 --> 1:16:17,198
You have sat here and voted guilty
with everyone else...


1424
1:16:17,198 --> 1:16:21,535
because there are some baseball tickets
burning a hole in your pocket.


1425
1:16:21,535 --> 1:16:26,791
And now you've changed your vote because you
say you're sick of all the talking here?


1426
1:16:26,791 --> 1:16:28,334
Now listen, buddy!


1427
1:16:28,334 --> 1:16:33,89
Who tells you that you have the right
to play like this with a man's life?


1428
1:16:33,89 --> 1:16:35,675
- Don't you care -
- Now wait a minute!


1429
1:16:35,675 --> 1:16:39,762
- You can't talk like that to me!
- I can talk like that to you.


1430
1:16:39,762 --> 1:16:41,722
If you want to vote not guilty...


1431
1:16:41,722 --> 1:16:44,183
then do it because you are convinced
the man is not guilty...


1432
1:16:44,183 --> 1:16:46,6
not because you've had enough.


1433
1:16:46,6 --> 1:16:48,729
And if you think he is guilty,
then vote that way.


1434
1:16:48,729 --> 1:16:52,24
Or don't you have the guts
to do what you think is right?


1435
1:16:52,24 --> 1:16:55,69
- Now listen.
- Guilty or not guilty?


1436
1:16:55,69 --> 1:17:0,324
- I told you, not guilty.
- Why?


1437
1:17:0,324 --> 1:17:2,34
Look, I don't have to...


1438
1:17:2,34 --> 1:17:5,246
You do have to! Say it! Why?


1439
1:17:5,246 --> 1:17:17,216
All right. I don't, uh, think he's guilty.


1440
1:17:17,216 --> 1:17:18,926
I want another vote.


1441
1:17:18,926 --> 1:17:21,512
Okay. There's another vote called for.


1442
1:17:21,512 --> 1:17:24,473
I guess the quickest way is a show of hands.
Anyone object?


1443
1:17:24,473 --> 1:17:28,311
Okay. All those voting not guilty,
raise your hands.


1444
1:17:28,311 --> 1:17:36,319
One, two, three, four,
five, six, seven...


1445
1:17:36,319 --> 1:17:41,907
eight.


1446
1:17:41,907 --> 1:17:45,36
Um, nine.


1447
1:17:45,36 --> 1:17:50,124
Um, all those voting guilty,
raise your hands.


1448
1:17:50,124 --> 1:17:52,585
One, two, three.


1449
1:17:52,585 --> 1:17:56,88
Well, the vote's nine to three
in favor of acquittal.


1450
1:17:56,88 --> 1:17:58,341
I don't understand you people!


1451
1:17:58,341 --> 1:18:0,593
I mean, all these picky little points
you keep bringing up.


1452
1:18:0,593 --> 1:18:4,13
They don't mean nothing!
You saw this kid just like I did.


1453
1:18:4,13 --> 1:18:7,6
You're not gonna tell me you believe
that phony story about losing the knife...


1454
1:18:7,6 --> 1:18:9,685
and that business
about being at the movies.


1455
1:18:9,685 --> 1:18:12,772
Look, you know how these people lie.
It's born in them.


1456
1:18:12,772 --> 1:18:14,899
I mean, what the heck.
I don't have to tell you.


1457
1:18:14,899 --> 1:18:16,942
They don't know what the truth is.


1458
1:18:16,942 --> 1:18:20,738
And let me tell you, they don't need
any real big reason to kill someone either.


1459
1:18:20,738 --> 1:18:22,573
No, sir.


1460
1:18:22,573 --> 1:18:25,701
They get drunk!
Oh, they're real big drinkers, all of 'em.


1461
1:18:25,701 --> 1:18:28,954
You know that.
And bang - someone's lying in the gutter.


1462
1:18:28,954 --> 1:18:32,41
Well, nobody's blaming them for it.
That's the way they are, by nature.


1463
1:18:32,41 --> 1:18:34,21
You know what I mean? Violent!


1464
1:18:34,21 --> 1:18:35,795
Where are you going?


1465
1:18:35,795 --> 1:18:39,799
Ηuman life don't mean
as much to them as it does to us.


1466
1:18:39,799 --> 1:18:42,885
Look! They're lushing it up
and fighting all the time...


1467
1:18:42,885 --> 1:18:44,97
and if somebody gets killed,
so somebody gets killed!


1468
1:18:44,97 --> 1:18:46,43
They don't care!


1469
1:18:46,43 --> 1:18:48,724
Oh, sure, there's some good things
about 'em too.


1470
1:18:48,724 --> 1:18:50,768
Look, I'm the first one to say that.


1471
1:18:50,768 --> 1:18:54,146
I've known a couple who were okay, but
that's the exception, you know what I mean?


1472
1:18:54,146 --> 1:18:57,983
Most of 'em, it's like they have no feelings.
They can do anything.


1473
1:18:57,983 --> 1:19:0,653
What's going on here?


1474
1:19:0,653 --> 1:19:2,78
I'm - I'm trying to tell ya...


1475
1:19:2,78 --> 1:19:4,865
you're making a big mistake, you people.


1476
1:19:4,865 --> 1:19:9,578
This kid is a liar!
I know it. I know all about them.


1477
1:19:9,578 --> 1:19:11,831
Listen to me.
They're no good.


1478
1:19:11,831 --> 1:19:16,21
There's not a one of 'em who's any good.


1479
1:19:16,21 --> 1:19:18,754
I mean, what -
What's happening in here?


1480
1:19:18,754 --> 1:19:22,216
I'm speaking my piece, and you...


1481
1:19:22,216 --> 1:19:24,969
Listen to me.


1482
1:19:24,969 --> 1:19:26,512
I...


1483
1:19:26,512 --> 1:19:29,56
We're - This kid on trial here, his type...


1484
1:19:29,56 --> 1:19:33,18
Well, don't you know about them?


1485
1:19:33,18 --> 1:19:36,564
Th-There's - There's a danger here.


1486
1:19:36,564 --> 1:19:38,732
These people are dangerous.


1487
1:19:38,732 --> 1:19:41,861
They're... wild.


1488
1:19:41,861 --> 1:19:43,863
Listen to me.


1489
1:19:43,863 --> 1:19:46,282
- Listen.
- I have.


1490
1:19:46,282 --> 1:19:53,205
Now sit down
and don't open your mouth again.


1491
1:19:53,205 --> 1:20:32,453
I was only trying to... tell you.


1492
1:20:32,453 --> 1:20:37,875
It's always difficult to keep personal
prejudice out of a thing like this.


1493
1:20:37,875 --> 1:20:43,464
Wherever you run into it,
prejudice always obscures the truth.


1494
1:20:43,464 --> 1:20:45,925
I don't really know what the truth is.


1495
1:20:45,925 --> 1:20:50,137
I don't suppose anybody
will ever really know.


1496
1:20:50,137 --> 1:20:54,183
Nine of us now seem to feel
that the defendant is innocent.


1497
1:20:54,183 --> 1:20:57,269
But we're just gambling on probabilities.


1498
1:20:57,269 --> 1:20:59,313
We may be wrong.


1499
1:20:59,313 --> 1:21:1,774
We may be trying to let
a guilty man go free.


1500
1:21:1,774 --> 1:21:3,317
I don't know.


1501
1:21:3,317 --> 1:21:5,402
Nobody really can.


1502
1:21:5,402 --> 1:21:7,863
But we have a reasonable doubt...


1503
1:21:7,863 --> 1:21:11,45
and that's something
that's very valuable in our system.


1504
1:21:11,45 --> 1:21:17,456
No jury can declare a man guilty
unless it's sure.


1505
1:21:17,456 --> 1:21:19,917
We nine can't understand...


1506
1:21:19,917 --> 1:21:23,462
how you three are still so sure.


1507
1:21:23,462 --> 1:21:26,84
- Maybe you can tell us.
- I'll try.


1508
1:21:26,84 --> 1:21:30,427
You've made some excellent points, but I
still believe the boy is guilty of murder...


1509
1:21:30,427 --> 1:21:32,221
and I have two reasons.


1510
1:21:32,221 --> 1:21:35,432
One, the evidence
given by the woman across the street...


1511
1:21:35,432 --> 1:21:38,143
who actually saw the murder committed.


1512
1:21:38,143 --> 1:21:40,813
As far as I'm concerned,
that's the most important testimony.


1513
1:21:40,813 --> 1:21:44,149
And two, the fact that she
described the stabbing by saying...


1514
1:21:44,149 --> 1:21:49,863
she saw the boy raise his arm over his head
and stab down into the father's chest.


1515
1:21:49,863 --> 1:21:51,991
She saw him do it the wrong way.


1516
1:21:51,991 --> 1:21:53,993
That's absolutely right.


1517
1:21:53,993 --> 1:21:56,662
Let's talk about this woman for a moment.


1518
1:21:56,662 --> 1:21:59,832
She said she went to bed
about 11:00 that night.


1519
1:21:59,832 --> 1:22:3,502
Her bed was next to the window,
and she could look out while lying down...


1520
1:22:3,502 --> 1:22:7,673
and see directly into the boy's room
across the street.


1521
1:22:7,673 --> 1:22:10,384
She tossed and turned for over an hour,
unable to sleep.


1522
1:22:10,384 --> 1:22:14,638
Finally, she turned toward the window
at about 10 minutes after 12:00...


1523
1:22:14,638 --> 1:22:19,852
and, as she looked out, she saw the killing
through the windows of a passing el train.


1524
1:22:19,852 --> 1:22:22,646
She said the lights went out
immediately after the killing...


1525
1:22:22,646 --> 1:22:28,444
but that she got a good look at the boy
in the act of stabbing his father.


1526
1:22:28,444 --> 1:22:33,32
As far as I can see it,
this is unshakable testimony.


1527
1:22:33,32 --> 1:22:41,81
- Well, that's the whole case.
- What do you think?


1528
1:22:41,81 --> 1:22:44,376
How about you?


1529
1:22:44,376 --> 1:22:46,92
I-I don't know.


1530
1:22:46,92 --> 1:22:49,6
So much evidence to sift.


1531
1:22:49,6 --> 1:22:51,5
This is a pretty complicated business.


1532
1:22:51,5 --> 1:22:54,928
Frankly, I don't see
how you can vote for acquittal.


1533
1:22:54,928 --> 1:22:57,348
It's not so easy to arrange
all the evidence in order.


1534
1:22:57,348 --> 1:22:59,475
You can throw out
all the other evidence!


1535
1:22:59,475 --> 1:23:3,145
The woman saw him do it!
What else do you want?


1536
1:23:3,145 --> 1:23:5,105
- Yeah, well, maybe -
- Let's vote on it.


1537
1:23:5,105 --> 1:23:7,358
Okay. There's another vote called for.


1538
1:23:7,358 --> 1:23:9,276
Anybody object?


1539
1:23:9,276 --> 1:23:12,404
All right. I'm changing my vote.
He's guilty.


1540
1:23:12,404 --> 1:23:14,907
Anybody else?
The vote is eight to four.


1541
1:23:14,907 --> 1:23:18,577
Why is this such a personal triumph
for you - this one vote?


1542
1:23:18,577 --> 1:23:22,122
Okay. I say we're a hung jury.
I say we take it in to the judge.


1543
1:23:22,122 --> 1:23:24,917
Ηow about it?
I want to hear arguments.


1544
1:23:24,917 --> 1:23:29,672
You, you're the leader of the cause.
What about it?


1545
1:23:29,672 --> 1:23:31,59
Let's go over it again.


1546
1:23:31,59 --> 1:23:33,592
We've been over it again!


1547
1:23:33,592 --> 1:23:38,472
The boy in the gray flannel suit here is bouncin'
backwards and forwards like a tennis ball.


1548
1:23:38,472 --> 1:23:44,269
No point in getting nasty
and trying to turn this into a contest.


1549
1:23:44,269 --> 1:23:45,813
Okay.


1550
1:23:45,813 --> 1:23:48,941
Maybe we can talk about
setting some kind of time limit.


1551
1:23:48,941 --> 1:23:51,777
Yeah, once around for the deal, huh?


1552
1:23:51,777 --> 1:23:55,614
It's a quarter after 6:00.


1553
1:23:55,614 --> 1:23:57,658
Someone before mentioned 7:00.


1554
1:23:57,658 --> 1:24:0,119
I think that's a point at which
we might begin to discuss...


1555
1:24:0,119 --> 1:24:3,455
the question of whether
we're a hung jury or not.


1556
1:24:3,455 --> 1:24:6,458
Don't you feel well?


1557
1:24:6,458 --> 1:24:8,502
I feel perfectly well, thank you.


1558
1:24:8,502 --> 1:24:11,296
I was saying that 7:00
would be a reasonable time.


1559
1:24:11,296 --> 1:24:14,299
Uh, the reason I asked about that
was because, uh...


1560
1:24:14,299 --> 1:24:15,968
you were rubbing your nose like...


1561
1:24:15,968 --> 1:24:18,721
Oh, I'm sorry for interrupting...


1562
1:24:18,721 --> 1:24:22,15
but you made a gesture
that reminded me of something.


1563
1:24:22,15 --> 1:24:24,143
I'm trying to settle something here.
Do you mind?


1564
1:24:24,143 --> 1:24:27,229
Well, I think this is important.


1565
1:24:27,229 --> 1:24:29,106
Thank you.


1566
1:24:29,106 --> 1:24:31,817
Now then,
I'm sure you'll pardon me for this...


1567
1:24:31,817 --> 1:24:34,82
but I was wondering why
you were rubbing your nose like that.


1568
1:24:34,82 --> 1:24:36,572
Oh, come on, will ya?


1569
1:24:36,572 --> 1:24:40,826
At this point, I happen to be talking
to the gentleman sitting next to you!


1570
1:24:40,826 --> 1:24:44,163
Now, why were you rubbing
your nose like that?


1571
1:24:44,163 --> 1:24:48,333
Well, if it's any of your business, I was
rubbing it because it bothers me a little.


1572
1:24:48,333 --> 1:24:50,43
Oh. I'm sorry.


1573
1:24:50,43 --> 1:24:54,6
- Is it - Is it because of your eyeglasses?
- It is.


1574
1:24:54,6 --> 1:24:55,841
Now can we get on to something else?


1575
1:24:55,841 --> 1:25:0,512
Your eyeglasses made those two
deep impressions on the sides of your nose.


1576
1:25:0,512 --> 1:25:2,765
I hadn't noticed that before.


1577
1:25:2,765 --> 1:25:6,351
- That must be annoying.
- It is very annoying.


1578
1:25:6,351 --> 1:25:8,353
Well, I wouldn't know about that.


1579
1:25:8,353 --> 1:25:11,774
I've never worn eyeglasses.
Twenty-twenty.


1580
1:25:11,774 --> 1:25:16,236
Listen, will you come on already
with the optometrist bit?


1581
1:25:16,236 --> 1:25:19,865
The woman who testified
that she saw the killing...


1582
1:25:19,865 --> 1:25:24,411
had those same marks
on the sides of her nose.


1583
1:25:24,411 --> 1:25:26,705
Holy smokes! You know, he's right.


1584
1:25:26,705 --> 1:25:28,457
Please.


1585
1:25:28,457 --> 1:25:32,294
Just give me a minute,
and I'll be finished.


1586
1:25:32,294 --> 1:25:35,214
I don't know if anyone else
noticed that about her.


1587
1:25:35,214 --> 1:25:40,135
I didn't think of it then,
but I've been going over her face...


1588
1:25:40,135 --> 1:25:42,346
in my mind.


1589
1:25:42,346 --> 1:25:45,349
She had those same marks.


1590
1:25:45,349 --> 1:25:50,562
- She kept rubbing them in court.
- He's right. She did do that a lot.


1591
1:25:50,562 --> 1:25:55,317
This woman was about, uh -
about 45 years old.


1592
1:25:55,317 --> 1:25:59,363
She was making a tremendous effort
to look 35...


1593
1:25:59,363 --> 1:26:1,657
for her first public appearance.


1594
1:26:1,657 --> 1:26:4,993
Heavy makeup, dyed hair...


1595
1:26:4,993 --> 1:26:8,956
brand-new clothes that should have
been worn by a younger woman.


1596
1:26:8,956 --> 1:26:10,707
No glasses.


1597
1:26:10,707 --> 1:26:12,459
No, women do that.


1598
1:26:12,459 --> 1:26:14,962
See if you can get the
mental picture of it.


1599
1:26:14,962 --> 1:26:16,88
What do you mean, no glasses?


1600
1:26:16,88 --> 1:26:19,675
How do you know whether she wore glasses?
Just 'cause she was rubbing her nose?


1601
1:26:19,675 --> 1:26:21,969
Now, she had those marks. I saw 'em.


1602
1:26:21,969 --> 1:26:23,971
So what?
What do ya think that means?


1603
1:26:23,971 --> 1:26:27,266
- Listen, I'm getting so sick of your yelling in here!
- Come on. Forget it.


1604
1:26:27,266 --> 1:26:30,352
Hey, listen. Listen, he's right.
I saw them too.


1605
1:26:30,352 --> 1:26:33,564
I was the closest one to her. She had these,
uh - these things on the side of her nose.


1606
1:26:33,564 --> 1:26:36,859
- What do you call those on the side?
- Well, what point are you making here?


1607
1:26:36,859 --> 1:26:40,821
She had dyed hair, marks on her nose.
Well, what does that mean?


1608
1:26:40,821 --> 1:26:48,704
Could those marks be made
by anything other than eyeglasses?


1609
1:26:48,704 --> 1:26:51,123
No, they couldn't.


1610
1:26:51,123 --> 1:26:54,751
I didn't see any marks!


1611
1:26:54,751 --> 1:26:56,545
I did.


1612
1:26:56,545 --> 1:26:59,172
Strange, but I didn't
think about it before.


1613
1:26:59,172 --> 1:27:1,383
Well, what about the lawyer?
Why didn't he say something?


1614
1:27:1,383 --> 1:27:4,386
There are 12 people in here
concentrating on this case.


1615
1:27:4,386 --> 1:27:6,555
Eleven of us didn't think of it either.


1616
1:27:6,555 --> 1:27:9,808
Well, what about the district attorney?
Do you think he'd pull a trick like that?


1617
1:27:9,808 --> 1:27:11,81
Have her testify without her glasses?


1618
1:27:11,81 --> 1:27:15,814
Did you ever see a woman who had to wear glasses and
didn't want to because she thinks they spoil her looks?


1619
1:27:15,814 --> 1:27:19,401
Okay. She had marks on her nose.


1620
1:27:19,401 --> 1:27:23,155
I'm giving you that.
From glasses, right?


1621
1:27:23,155 --> 1:27:27,409
She didn't want to wear 'em out of the house
so people would think she's gorgeous.


1622
1:27:27,409 --> 1:27:32,8
But when she saw this kid killing his
father, she was in the house alone.


1623
1:27:32,8 --> 1:27:34,374
That's all.


1624
1:27:34,374 --> 1:27:40,88
- Do you wear glasses when you go to bed?
- No, I don't.


1625
1:27:40,88 --> 1:27:42,9
No one wears eyeglasses to bed.


1626
1:27:42,9 --> 1:27:45,177
It's logical to assume that she wasn't
wearing them when she was in bed...


1627
1:27:45,177 --> 1:27:47,12
tossing and turning, trying to fall asleep.


1628
1:27:47,12 --> 1:27:49,431
- How do you know?
- I don't know! I'm guessing.


1629
1:27:49,431 --> 1:27:51,975
I'm also guessing that she probably
didn't put her glasses on...


1630
1:27:51,975 --> 1:27:54,186
when she turned
to look casually out of the window.


1631
1:27:54,186 --> 1:27:57,22
And she herself testified the killing
took place just as she looked out.


1632
1:27:57,22 --> 1:28:0,15
The lights went off a split second later.
She couldn't have had time to put them on then.


1633
1:28:0,15 --> 1:28:1,86
- Wait a second.
- Here's another guess.


1634
1:28:1,86 --> 1:28:6,31
Maybe she honestly thought she saw the boy
kill his father. I say she only saw a blur.


1635
1:28:6,31 --> 1:28:9,701
How do you know what she saw?
How does he know all that?


1636
1:28:9,701 --> 1:28:12,537
How do you know what kind of glasses she wore?
Maybe they were sunglasses.


1637
1:28:12,537 --> 1:28:15,248
Maybe she was farsighted.
What do you know about it?


1638
1:28:15,248 --> 1:28:18,585
I only know the woman's eyesight
is in question now.


1639
1:28:18,585 --> 1:28:24,8
She had to be able to identify a person
60 feet away, at night, without glasses.


1640
1:28:24,8 --> 1:28:27,26
You can't send someone off to die
on evidence like that.


1641
1:28:27,26 --> 1:28:29,346
Oh, don't give me that.


1642
1:28:29,346 --> 1:28:31,598
Don't you think the woman
might have made a mistake?


1643
1:28:31,598 --> 1:28:34,101
- No.
- It's not possible?


1644
1:28:34,101 --> 1:28:38,689
No, it's not possible.


1645
1:28:38,689 --> 1:28:41,733
Is it possible?


1646
1:28:41,733 --> 1:28:47,572
Not guilty.


1647
1:28:47,572 --> 1:28:50,325
Do you think he's guilty?


1648
1:28:50,325 --> 1:28:55,8
I think he's guilty.


1649
1:28:55,8 --> 1:28:59,626
Do you?


1650
1:28:59,626 --> 1:29:2,754
No. I'm convinced.


1651
1:29:2,754 --> 1:29:4,423
Not guilty.


1652
1:29:4,423 --> 1:29:6,299
What's the matter with you?


1653
1:29:6,299 --> 1:29:8,301
I have a reasonable doubt now.


1654
1:29:8,301 --> 1:29:9,928
Eleven to one.


1655
1:29:9,928 --> 1:29:12,931
Well, what about all the other evidence?
What about all that stuff?


1656
1:29:12,931 --> 1:29:15,1
The knife, the whole business!


1657
1:29:15,1 --> 1:29:23,775
Well, you said we could throw out
all the other evidence.


1658
1:29:23,775 --> 1:29:28,947
Well, what do we do now?


1659
1:29:28,947 --> 1:29:30,699
You're alone.


1660
1:29:30,699 --> 1:29:37,706
I don't care whether I'm alone or not!
It's my right.


1661
1:29:37,706 --> 1:29:49,9
It's your right.


1662
1:29:49,9 --> 1:29:53,55
Well, what do you want?
I say he's guilty.


1663
1:29:53,55 --> 1:29:57,392
- We want to hear your arguments.
- I gave you my arguments.


1664
1:29:57,392 --> 1:29:59,603
We're not convinced.


1665
1:29:59,603 --> 1:30:2,481
We want to hear them again.


1666
1:30:2,481 --> 1:30:10,155
We have as much time as it takes.


1667
1:30:10,155 --> 1:30:14,701
Everything - Every single thing
that took place in that courtroom...


1668
1:30:14,701 --> 1:30:16,703
but I mean everything -
says he's guilty.


1669
1:30:16,703 --> 1:30:20,832
What do you think,
I'm an idiot or something?


1670
1:30:20,832 --> 1:30:23,1
Why don't you take that stuff
about the old man?


1671
1:30:23,1 --> 1:30:27,839
The old man who lived there
and heard everything.


1672
1:30:27,839 --> 1:30:29,591
Or this business about the knife.


1673
1:30:29,591 --> 1:30:31,676
What? 'Cause he found another one
exactly like it?


1674
1:30:31,676 --> 1:30:35,97
The old man saw him
right there on the stairs!


1675
1:30:35,97 --> 1:30:39,101
What's the difference
how many seconds it was?


1676
1:30:39,101 --> 1:30:42,521
Every single thing.


1677
1:30:42,521 --> 1:30:45,774
The knife falling through
a hole in his pocket.


1678
1:30:45,774 --> 1:30:49,194
You can't prove he didn't get to the door.


1679
1:30:49,194 --> 1:30:51,696
Sure, you can take all the time,
hobble around the room.


1680
1:30:51,696 --> 1:30:56,201
But you can't prove it!


1681
1:30:56,201 --> 1:30:59,913
And what about this business
of the el and the movies?


1682
1:30:59,913 --> 1:31:3,41
There's a phony deal
if I ever heard one.


1683
1:31:3,41 --> 1:31:7,337
I'll bet ya $5,000
I'd remember the movies I saw.


1684
1:31:7,337 --> 1:31:9,673
I'm telling ya,
everything that's gone on...


1685
1:31:9,673 --> 1:31:13,593
has been twisted and turned!


1686
1:31:13,593 --> 1:31:15,762
This business with the glasses?


1687
1:31:15,762 --> 1:31:21,393
How do you know she didn't have them on?
This woman testified in open court!


1688
1:31:21,393 --> 1:31:25,438
And what about hearing the kid yell, huh?


1689
1:31:25,438 --> 1:31:29,86
I'm telling ya, I've got
all the facts here.


1690
1:31:29,86 --> 1:31:34,114
Here. Ah...


1691
1:31:34,114 --> 1:31:43,832
Well, that's it!
That's the whole case.


1692
1:31:43,832 --> 1:31:47,711
Well?


1693
1:31:47,711 --> 1:31:54,843
Say something!


1694
1:31:54,843 --> 1:31:59,97
You lousy bunch of bleeding hearts.


1695
1:31:59,97 --> 1:32:1,99
You're not gonna intimidate me.


1696
1:32:1,99 --> 1:32:6,98
I'm entitled to my opinion.


1697
1:32:6,98 --> 1:32:16,114
Rotten kids.
You work your life out!


1698
1:32:16,114 --> 1:32:22,746
I can't keep...


1699
1:32:22,746 --> 1:32:28,293
No.


1700
1:32:28,293 --> 1:32:33,506
Not guilty.


1701
1:32:33,506 --> 1:32:38,178
Not guilty.


1702
1:32:38,178 --> 1:32:50,357
Not...


1703
1:32:50,357 --> 1:34:46,181
Um, we're ready now.


1704
1:34:46,181 --> 1:34:52,187
Hey!


1705
1:34:52,187 --> 1:34:53,938
What's your name?


1706
1:34:53,938 --> 1:34:55,523
Davis.


1707
1:34:55,523 --> 1:34:59,778
My name's McCardle.


1708
1:34:59,778 --> 1:35:1,529
Well, so long.


1709
1:35:1,529 --> 1:37:1,529
So long.


